text.Grail1963:
.2 Lord, do not reprove me in your anger;
punish me not in your rage.
.3 Have mercy on me, Lord, I have no strength;
Lord, heal me, my body is racked;
.4 my soul is racked with pain.
But you, O Lord...how long?
.5 Return, Lord, rescue my soul.

Save me in your merciful love;
.6 for in death no one remembers you;
from the grave, who can give you praise?
.7 I am exhausted with my groaning;
every night I drench my pillow with tears;
I bedew my bed with weeping.
.8 My eye wastes away with grief;
I have grown old surrounded by my foes.
.9 Leave me, all you who do evil;
for the Lord has heard my weeping.
.10 The Lord has heard my plea;
The Lord will accept my prayer.
.11 All my foes will retire in confusion,
foiled and suddenly confounded.

text.JPS1985:
15:1 A psalm of David. LORD, who may sojourn in Your tent, who may dwell on Your holy mountain?
15:2 He who lives without blame, who does what is right, and in his heart acknowledges the truth;
15:3 whose tongue is not given to evil; who has never done harm to his fellow, or borne reproach for [his acts toward] his neighbor;
15:4 for whom a contemptible man is abhorrent, but who honors those who fear the LORD; who stands by his oath even to his hurt;
15:5 who has never lent money at interest, or accepted a bribe against the innocent. The man who acts thus shall never be shaken.

text.Grail1963:
1 Lord, who shall be admitted to your tent
and dwell on your holy mountain?
2 He who walks without fault;
he who acts with justice
and speaks the truth from his heart;
3 he who does not slander with his tongue;
He who does no wrong to his brother,
who casts no slur on his neighbor,
4 who holds the godless in disdain,
but honors those who fear the Lord;
he who keeps his pledge, come what may;
5 who takes no interest on a loan
and accepts no bribes against the innocent.
Such a man will stand firm forever.

text.Rotherham:
15:1 O Yahweh! Who shall be a guest in thy tent? Who shall abide in thy holy mountain?
15:2 He that walketh without blame, and doeth what is right, and speaketh truth with his heart;
15:3 Hath not carried slander on his tongue, hath not done his friend a wrong, nor, a reproach, taken up against his neighbour;
15:4 Despised in his sight, is the reprobate, but, them who revere Yahweh, he doth honour, he hath sworn to his neighbour, and will not change;
15:5 His silver, hath he not put out on interest, nor, a bribe against the innocent, hath he taken. He that doeth these things, shall not be shaken unto times age-abiding.

text.NABRE:
15:1 Psalm 15 The Righteous Israelite - A psalm of David. I - LORD, who may abide in your tent? Who may dwell on your holy mountain?
15:2 II - Whoever walks without blame, doing what is right, speaking truth from the heart;
15:3 Who does not slander with his tongue, does no harm to a friend, never defames a neighbor;
15:4 Who disdains the wicked, but honors those who fear the LORD; Who keeps an oath despite the cost,
15:5 lends no money at interest, accepts no bribe against the innocent. III - Whoever acts like this shall never be shaken.

text.NRSV:
20:1 May the Lord answer you in the day of trouble, the Name of the God of Jacob defend you;
20:2 Send you help from his sanctuary and strengthen you out of Zion;
20:3 Remember all your offerings and accept your burnt sacrifice;
20:4 Grant you your heart's desire and prosper all your plans.
20:5 We will shout for joy at your victory and triumph in the Name of our God; may the Lord grant all your requests.
20:6 Now I know that the Lord gives victory to his anointed; he will answer him out of his holy heaven, with the victorious might of his right hand.
20:7 Some put their trust in chariots and some in horses, but we will call upon the Name of the Lord our God.
20:8 They are brought down and fallen, but we are risen and stand upright.
20:9 O Lord, give victory to the king and answer us when we call.

text.Rotherham:
26:1 Do me justice, O Yahweh, For, I, in my blamelessness, have walked, and, in Yahweh, have I trusted, I will not waver.
26:2 Try me, O Yahweh, and prove me, Test my reins and my heart:—
26:3 For, thy lovingkindness, hath been before mine eyes, and I have walked to and fro in thy faithfulness;
26:4 I have not sat with men of deceit, nor, with dissemblers, would I enter;
26:5 I have hated the convocation of evil-doers, and, with lawless men, would I not sit;
26:6 I will bathe, in pureness, my hands,—so will I go in procession around thine altar, O Yahweh;
26:7 To sound aloud a song, and to recount all thy wonderful doings.
26:8 O Yahweh, I have loved the asylum of thy house, even the place of the habitation of thy glory!
26:9 Do not remove, with sinners, my soul, nor, with men of bloodshed, my life;
26:10 In whose hands is a plot, and, their right hand, is filled with a bribe.
26:11 But, I, in my blamelessness, will walk, Redeem me and show me favour.
26:12 My foot standeth in a level place, In the convocations, will I bless Yahweh.

29:1 Give to Yahweh, ye sons of the mighty,—Give to Yahweh, [both] glory and strength:
29:2 Give to Yahweh, the glory of his Name, Bow down to Yahweh, in the adornment of holiness.
29:3 The voice of Yahweh, is upon the waters,—The GOD of glory, hath thundered, Yahweh, is upon mighty waters;
29:4 The voice of Yahweh, is with power, The voice of Yahweh, is with majesty;
29:5 The voice of Yahweh, is breaking cedars, Now hath Yahweh, broken down, the cedars of Lebanon!
29:6 And hath made them leap like a calf, Lebanon and Sirion, like the bull-calf of wild-oxen;
29:7 The voice of Yahweh, is cleaving out flames of fire;
29:8 The voice of Yahweh, bringeth birth-pains upon the wilderness; Yahweh bringeth birth-pains upon the wilderness of Kadesh!
29:9 The voice of Yahweh, causeth the gazelles to bring forth, and hath stript forests; and, in his own temple, every one there, is saying, Glory!
29:10 Yahweh, at the Flood, was seated, And Yahweh hath taken his seat, as king, unto times age-abiding.
29:11 Yahweh, will give, strength to his people,—Yahweh, will bless his people with prosperity.

54:1 O God! by thine own Name, save me, And, by thine own strength, wilt thou vindicate me?
54:2 O God! Hear my prayer, Give ear to the sayings of my mouth;
54:3 For, aliens, have risen up against me, And, men of violence, have sought my life, They have not set God before them. [Selah.]
54:4 Lo! God, is bringing me help, My Lord, is with the upholders of my life;
54:5 Let him turn back the mischief upon mine adversaries, In thy faithfulness, destroy them!
54:6 With a freewill-offering, will I sacrifice unto thee, I will praise thy Name, O Yahweh, for it is good;
54:7 For, out of all distress, hath he rescued me,—And, upon my foes, hath, mine own eye, looked.

text.Grail1963:
.2 Do you truly speak justice, you who hold divine power?
Do you mete out fair judgment to the sons of men?
.3 No, in your hearts you devise injustice;
your hands deal out violence to the land.
.4 In their wickedness they have gone astray from their birth;
they wandered among lies as soon as they were born.
.5 Their venom is like the venom of the snake;
they are heedless as the adder that turns a deaf ear
.6 lest it should catch the snakecharmer's voice,
the voice of the skillful dealer in spells.
.7 O God, break the teeth in their mouths,
tear out the fangs of these wild beasts, O Lord!
.8 Let them vanish like water that runs away;
let them wither like grass that is trodden under foot:
.9 let them be like the snail that dissolves into slime;
like a woman's miscarriage that never sees the sun.
.10 Before they put forth thorns, like a bramble,
let them be swept away, green wood or dry!

.11 The just shall rejoice at the sight of vengeance;
they shall bathe their feet in the blood of the wicked.
.12 "Truly", men shall say, "the just are rewarded.
Truly there is a God who does justice on the earth."

text.Rotherham:
69:1 Save me, O God, For waters have entered as far as the life;
69:2 I have sunk in deep swamp, Where there is no place to stand, I have come into abysses of waters, Where a flood hath overflowed me;
69:3 I am weary with mine outcry, Parched is my throat,—Mine eyes have become dim, through waiting for my God.
69:4 More than the hairs of my head, Are they who hate me without cause,—Firmer than my bones, Are they who are my foes for false cause,—What I had not plundered, then, had I to restore.
69:5 O God, thou, hast known my folly, And, my wrong-doings, from thee, have not been hid.
69:6 Let them not be ashamed, through me, Who have waited for thee, O My Lord, Yahweh of hosts,—Let them not be confounded, through me, Who are seeking thee, O God of Israel!
69:7 Because, for thy sake, have I borne reproach, Confusion hath covered my face;
69:8 One estranged, have I become, to my own brethren, Yea, an alien, to the sons of my own mother;
69:9 Because, zeal for thy house, hath eaten me up, And, the reproaches of them who have reproached thee, have fallen upon me.
69:10 When I have humbled my soul with fasting, Then hath it turned to my reproach;
69:11 When I have made my clothing of sackcloth, Then have I served them for a by-word;
69:12 They who sit in the gate talk against me,—And [against me are] the songs of them who imbibe strong drink.
69:13 But, as for me, my prayer shall be unto thee, O Yahweh, in a time of acceptance, O God, in the abounding of thy lovingkindness, answer me with thy saving faithfulness.
69:14 Rescue me out of the mire, lest I sink, Let me be rescued, From my haters, and, From abysses of waters:
69:15 Let not a flood of waters overflow me, And let not the depth swallow me up, Neither let the well close, over me, her mouth.
69:16 Answer me, O Yahweh, for good is thy lovingkindness, According to the abounding of thy compassions, turn thou towards me:
69:17 Then do not hide thy face from thy servant, Because I am in distress, haste thou—answer me!
69:18 Oh draw near unto my soul—redeem it, Because of mine enemies, ransom me.
69:19 Thou, knowest my reproach, and my shame, and my confusion, Before thee, are all mine adversaries.
69:20 Reproach hath broken my heart, and I am weak,—Though I waited for one to pity me, yet there was none, And for comforters, yet I found not any.
69:21 But they put in my food—poison! And, for my thirst, they gave for my drink—vinegar!
69:22 Let their table, before them, become a snare, And unto their friends, a lure;
69:23 Let their eyes become too dim to see, And, their loins, continually cause thou to shake;
69:24 Pour out over them thine indignation, And let, the glow of thine anger, overtake them:
69:25 Let their encampment become desolate, In their tents, be there none to dwell:
69:26 For, whom, thou thyself, hadst smitten, they pursued, And, unto the pain of thy wounded ones, they must needs add.
69:27 Lay punishment on their iniquity, And let them not enter into thy righteousness;
69:28 Let them be blotted out of the book of life, And, with the righteous, let them not be enrolled.
69:29 I, then, am humbled and in pain, Thy salvation, O God, may it set me on high.
69:30 I will praise the Name of God with a song, And will magnify him with thanksgiving;
69:31 So shall it be more pleasing to Yahweh than a bullock of the herd, Showing horn [and] divided hoof.
69:32 The humbled have seen—they rejoice! Ye seekers of God, let your heart, then, revive;
69:33 For, a Hearkener to the needy, is Yahweh, And, his prisoners, hath he not despised.
69:34 Let the heavens and the earth, praise him, The seas, and everything that creepeth therein.
69:35 For, God, will save Zion, And build the cities of Judah, So shall men dwell there, and possess it:
69:36 Yea, the seed of his servants, shall inherit it, And, the lovers of his Name, shall settle down therein.

71:1 In thee, O Yahweh, have I sought refuge, May I not be ashamed unto times age-abiding:
71:2 In thy righteousness, wilt thou rescue me, and deliver me, Incline unto me thine ear, and save me:
71:3 Be thou unto me, a Rock to dwell in, a Place of Security, To save me, For, my mountain crag and my stronghold, thou art.
71:4 Oh my God, deliver me, From the hand of the lawless one, From the clutch of the perverse and ruthless one;
71:5 For, thou, art my hope, My Lord, Yahweh, My confidence from my youthful days:
71:6 Upon thee, have I stayed myself from birth, Thou art he that severed me, from the body of my mother, Of thee, shall be my praise—continually.
71:7 A very wonder, have I been unto many, Seeing that, thou, hast been my strong refuge,
71:8 My mouth shall be filled with, thy praise, All the day, with thy splendour.
71:9 Do not cast me off in the time of old age, When my vigour faileth, do not forsake me;
71:10 For mine enemies have spoken of me, And, they who watch for my life, have taken counsel together;
71:11 Saying, God, hath forsaken him, Pursue and take him, For there is none to rescue.
71:12 O God, be not far from me, O my God, to help me, make haste!
71:13 Let them be ashamed—be consumed, Who are assailing my life,—Let them be covered with reproach and confusion, Who are seeking my hurt.
71:14 But, I, continually will hope, And will add to all thy praise;
71:15 My mouth, shall relate thy righteousness, All the day, thy deliverance, For I know not the numbers.
71:16 I will enter into the mighty doings of My Lord—Yahweh, I will make mention of thy righteousness—thine alone.
71:17 O God, thou hast taught me from my youthful days, And, hitherto, have I been wont to tell of thy wonders;
71:18 Even now, therefore, that I am old and grayheaded, O God, do not forsake me,—Until I tell of thine arm unto a [new] generation, Unto every one that is to come, thy might;
71:19 And, as for thy righteousness, O God, up on high, Wherein thou hast wrought great things, O God! who is like unto thee?
71:20 Thou who hast let us see many distresses and misfortunes, Wilt again bring us to life, And, out of the resounding depths of the earth, wilt again raise us up;
71:21 Thou wilt increase my greatness, And, on every side, wilt comfort me.
71:22 I also, will praise thee by the aid of a harp, Thy faithfulness, O my God,—I will make music unto thee with a lyre, Thou holy one of Israel;
71:23 My lips shall make a joyful noise, When I make music unto thee, And my soul which thou hast ransomed;
71:24 Even my tongue, all the day, shall softly utter thy righteousness, For they have turned pale—for they have blushed, Who were seeking my hurt.

72:1 O God! thy justice, give, unto the king, And thy righteousness, unto the son of a king;
72:2 May he judge, Thy people with righteousness; And thine oppressed ones with justice;
72:3 May the mountains bring peace to the people, And the hills [be laden] with righteousness;
72:4 May he, Vindicate the oppressed of the people, Bring deliverance to the children of the needy, and, Crush the oppressor.
72:5 Let men revere thee, With the sun, And in presence of the moon, Unto the remotest generation.
72:6 Let him come down, Like rain on fields to be mown, Like myriad drops on land to be reaped.
72:7 May righteousness, in his days, blossom forth, And abundance of peace, till there be no moon.
72:8 So let him have dominion, From sea to sea, And from the River [="Euphrates"] unto the ends of the earth;
72:9 Before him, let the men of the desert kneel, But, as for his foes, the dust, let them lick;
72:10 The kings of Tarshish and of the Coastlands, A gift, let them render, The kings of Sheba and Seba, A present, let them bring;
72:11 Yea let all kings, bow down unto him, Let, all nations, serve him;
72:12 Because he Rescueth, The needy from the rich, The oppressed, who hath no helper;
72:13 He Pitieth the weak and the needy, And, the lives of the needy, he Saveth:
72:14 From extortion, and, violence, he Redeemeth their life, And precious is their blood in his sight.
72:15 Let him live, then! And be there given unto him of the gold of Sheba,—Let prayer also be offered for him continually, All the day, let him be blessed.
72:16 May there be an abundance of corn in the earth, in the top of the mountains,—Let the fruit thereof, wave like Lebanon, And they of the city bloom like the fresh shoots of the earth.
72:17 May his Name be age-abiding, In the presence of the sun, let his Name flourish,—And may all the families of the ground bless themselves in him, All nations, pronounce him happy!
72:18 Blessed be Yahweh God, the God of Israel,—Who doeth wondrous things by himself alone;
72:19 And blessed be his glorious Name, unto times age-abiding,—And filled with his glory be all the earth, Amen and Amen!
72:20 Ended are the prayers of David, son of Jesse.

73:1 Nothing but good, is God, Unto Israel, Unto the pure in heart.
73:2 But, as for me,—My feet had, almost stumbled, My steps had, well-nigh slipped;
73:3 For I was envious of the boasters, At the prosperity of the lawless, used I to look.
73:4 For they have no pangs in their death, And vigorous is their body;
73:5 Of the toil of weak mortals, have they none, Nor, with the sons of earth, are they hard smitten.
73:6 For this cause, doth arrogance deck them as a neck-chain, And a garment of wrong is their attire;
73:7 Their iniquity, hath proceeded from fatness, They have surpassed the imaginations of the heart;
73:8 They mock, and wickedly command oppression, From on high, they command;
73:9 They have set, in the heavens, their mouth, And, their tongue, marcheth through the earth.
73:10 Therefore must his people return thither, And, the waters of abundance, are drained by them;
73:11 And they say—How doth GOD know? And is there knowledge in the Most High?
73:12 Lo! these, are the lawless, Who are secure for an age, They have attained unto wealth.
73:13 Altogether in vain, Have I cleansed my heart, And bathed in pureness, my hands;
73:14 And yet been smitten all the day, And been rebuked morning by morning!
73:15 If I had thought, I will relate it thus, Lo! the circle of thy sons, had I betrayed.
73:16 When I reasoned, that I might understand this, A vexation, it was in mine eyes:
73:17 Until I could enter the holy places of God,—Could give heed to their hereafter:—
73:18 Surely, in slippery places, dost thou set them,—Thou hast suffered them to fall into places of danger.
73:19 How have they become desolate, as in a moment! They have ceased—come to an end, by reason of calamities.
73:20 As the dream of him that waketh, O my Lord! when rousing thyself up, their shadowy being, wilt thou despise.
73:21 But my heart had grown embittered, And, in my reins, had I received wounds;
73:22 But, I, was brutish, and could not perceive, Like the beasts, had I become before thee.
73:23 Nevertheless, I, am continually before thee, Thou hast taken hold of my right hand;
73:24 By thy counsel, wilt thou guide me, And, afterwards, unto glory, wilt thou take me.
73:25 Whom have I in the heavens? And, compared with thee, there is nothing I desire on earth.
73:26 Failed have my flesh and my heart, The rock of my heart—and my portion, is God unto times age-abiding.
73:27 For lo! they who are far from thee, shall perish, Thou hast put an end to every one who wandered unchastely from thee.
73:28 But, as for me, the drawing near of God, is my blessedness,—I have made, of My Lord Yahweh, my refuge,—That I may recount all thy works.

75:1 We have given thanks unto thee, O God, we have given thanks, And, in calling upon thy Name, men have recounted thy wonders.
75:2 Surely I will take a set time,—I, with equity, will judge:
75:3 Earth was melting away with all its inhabitants, I, have fixed the pillars thereof. [Selah.]
75:4 I have said to the boasters, Do not boast, And to the lawless, Do not lift up a horn;
75:5 Do not lift up on high your horn, Nor speak of the Rock, with arrogance;
75:6 For neither from east nor west, Nor from the wilderness of the mountains [cometh exaltation] ;
75:7 For, God himself, is about to judge, One, he will cast down, Another, he will lift up;
75:8 For, a cup, is in the hand of Yahweh, Whose wine is foaming, It is full of spiced wine, Which he hath caused to flow from one to another,—Surely, the dregs thereof, they shall drain out—they shall drink, Even all the lawless ones of the earth.
75:9 But, I, will exult unto times age-abiding, I will sing praises unto the God of Jacob;
75:10 But, all the horns of the lawless, will I hew off,—Exalted shall be the horns of the Righteous One.

77:1 With my voice—unto God, will I make outcry, With my voice unto God, and he will give ear unto me;
77:2 In the day of my distress—unto My Lord, will I seek, My hand, by night, hath been outstretched and never once became slack, My soul, hath refused to be consoled;
77:3 I remember God and I murmur, I muse, and my spirit swooneth. [Selah.]
77:4 Thou hast held, watching, mine eyes, I was driven to and fro, and could not speak;
77:5 I reasoned, Of the days of aforetime, Of the years of by-gone ages;
77:6 I remember my song in the night,—With my own heart, I commune, And my spirit, maketh search:—
77:7 For ages, will My Lord reject? And, not again, grant acceptance any more?
77:8 Hath his lovingkindness, come to a perpetual end? Hath his word failed to generation after generation?
77:9 Hath GOD, forgotten to show favour? Or hath he shut up, in anger, his compassions? [Selah.]
77:10 Then said I—An affliction to me, it is, The changing of the right hand of the Most High.
77:11 I will remember the doings of Yah, Surely I will remember, out of aforetime, thy wonderful way;
77:12 And will talk to myself of all thy work, And, of thy doings, will I muse:—
77:13 O God, in the sanctuary, is thy way,—Who is a great GOD like Elohim?
77:14 Thou, art GOD, doing wonderfully,—Thou hast made known, among the peoples, thy might;
77:15 Thou didst redeem, with thine arm—Thy people, Thy sons of Jacob and Joseph. [Selah.]
77:16 The waters saw thee, O God, The waters saw thee, They were in birth-throes, Yea the resounding deeps were stirred;
77:17 The clouds, poured down waters, The skies uttered, a voice, Yea, thine arrows, flew hither and thither;
77:18 The, voice of thy thunder, was in the whirlwind, Thy lightnings illumined the world, The earth, trembled and quaked;
77:19 In the sea, was thy way, And, thy path, in the mighty waters, And, thy footprints, could not be known:
77:20 Thou didst lead, like a flock, thy people, By the hand of Moses and Aaron.

78:1 Give ear, O my people, to mine instruction, Bend your ear to the sayings of my mouth;
78:2 I will open, in a parable, my mouth, I will pour forth enigmas out of antiquity;—
78:3 Which we have heard, and come to know, And, our fathers, have recounted to us;
78:4 We will not withhold [them] from their children, To a later generation, recounting the praises of Yahweh, Even his might and his wonders which he wrought;
78:5 When he set up a testimony in Jacob, And, a law, appointed in Israel,—Which he commanded our fathers, That they might make them known to their children;
78:6 To the end, A later generation, might come to know, Children who should be born, Who should arise, and recount [them] to their children;
78:7 That they might set, in Elohim, their confidence,—And not forget the doings of El, But, his commandments, might observe;
78:8 And not become, like their fathers, a generation stubborn and rebellious,—A generation that fixed not their heart, Neither was their spirit, faithful with GOD.
78:9 The sons of Ephraim—armed bowmen, Turned in the day of battle;
78:10 They kept not the covenant of God, And, in his law, refused to walk;
78:11 And forgat His doings, And his wonders which he had showed them:
78:12 In presence of their fathers, wrought he, wondrously,—In the land of Egypt—the field of Zoan:
78:13 He clave the sea, and caused them to pass through, And reared up the waters like a mound;
78:14 And led them, by a cloud, in the daytime, And all the night, by a light of fire;
78:15 He used to cleave rocks in the desert, And let them drink as out of mighty deeps;
78:16 And he brought forth streams out of the cliff, And caused waters to flow down, like rivers.
78:17 But again, once more sinned they against him, Resisting the Most High in a land of drought:
78:18 They put GOD to the proof in their heart, By asking food to their mind:
78:19 Yea they spake against Elohim,—They said, Can GOD prepare a table in the desert?
78:20 Lo! he hath smitten a rock, And waters, have gushed out, Yea, torrents, have rushed along,—Food also, can he give? Or provide flesh for his people?
78:21 Therefore, Yahweh hearkened, and became wroth,—And, a fire, was kindled against Jacob, Moreover also, anger, mounted against Israel;
78:22 Because, They believed not in God, Nor trusted in his salvation;
78:23 Though he had commanded the skies above, And, the doors of the heavens, had opened;
78:24 And had rained on them manna to eat, And, the corn of the heavens, had given to them:
78:25 The food of the mighty, each one did eat, Nourishment, sent he them to the full;
78:26 He let loose an east wind in the heavens, Then guided he, in his might, a south wind;
78:27 And rained upon them flesh as the dust, And, like the sand of the seas, birds of wing;
78:28 And let them fall in the midst of their camp,—Round about their habitations.
78:29 So they did eat and were abundantly filled, When, what they longed for, he had brought them:—
78:30 They had not turned away from what they had longed for, Yet was their food in their mouth,
78:31 When, the anger of God, mounted against them, And he slew of their vigorous youths, And, the choice young men of Israel, caused he to bow down in death.
78:32 For all this, sinned they still, And believed not in his wonders;
78:33 So he ended, in a breath, their days, And their years, in a sudden terror!
78:34 If he slew [of] them, then they sought him, Yea they turned, and did earnestly seek GOD;
78:35 And remembered that, Elohim, was their rock, Yea, EL Most High, their Redeemer:
78:36 So they spake him fair with their mouth, And, with their tongue, did promise him falsely;
78:37 But, their heart, was not fixed with him, Nor were they trusty in his covenant:
78:38 Yet, he, full of compassion, would put a propitiatory-covering over iniquity, and not destroy,—Yea, many a time, turned he back his anger, And would not stir up all his wrath.
78:39 So then he remembered, That, Flesh, they were, A Wind departing, that returneth not.
78:40 How often they, Resisted him in the desert, Vexed him, in the waste:
78:41 Yea they again put GOD to the test, And, to the Holy One of Israel, caused they sorrow:
78:42 They remembered not his hand—The day, When he ransomed them from the adversary;
78:43 When he set, in Egypt, his signs, And his wonders, in the plain of Zoan;
78:44 When he turned, into blood, their Nile-streams, And, their own rivers, could they not drink;
78:45 He sent among them, The gad-fly, and it devoured them, And the frog, and it despoiled them;
78:46 When he gave to the corn-locust their produce, And their toil, to the swarming locust;
78:47 He killed, with hail, their vine, And their sycomores, with frost:
78:48 When he gave up, to hail-storms, their beasts, And their cattle, to pestilent fevers;
78:49 He sent among them the heat of his anger, Wrath and indignation and distress,—A mission of messengers of misfortune:
78:50 He leveled a path for his anger, Withheld not, from death, their soul, But, their life—to the pestilence, he delivered:
78:51 So he smote, Every first-born in Egypt, The beginning of their strength, in the tents of Ham;
78:52 And he set forth, like sheep, his people, And guided them, like a flock in the desert;
78:53 Yea he led them securely, and they dreaded not, And, their enemies, the sea did cover.
78:54 Then brought he them within his own holy bounds, The mountain-range, which his right hand made his own:
78:55 So he drave out, before them, [whole] nations, And allotted them, by line, an inheritance, And caused to dwell, in their own homes, the tribes of Israel.
78:56 But they tested and resisted God Most High, And, his testimonies, did not observe;
78:57 But drew back and dealt treacherously, like their fathers, They turned aside, like deceitful bowmen;
78:58 And provoked him to anger with their high places, And, with their images, used to move him to jealousy.
78:59 God heard and was wroth, And greatly abhorred Israel;
78:60 So he gave up the habitation of Shiloh, The tent he had set up among Men;
78:61 Yea he gave up, into captivity, his strength, And his beauty into the hand of an adversary;
78:62 And delivered up, to the sword, his people, And, with his own inheritance, was he wroth;
78:63 His young men, were devoured by fire, And, his virgins, were not praised in song;
78:64 His priests, by the sword, did fall, And, his widows, were not able to bewail.
78:65 Then awoke, as one that had slept, Adonay, As a warrior exulting with wine!
78:66 So he smote his adversaries in the rear, Reproach age-abiding, laid he upon them.
78:67 Howbeit he rejected the tent of Joseph, And, the tribe of Ephraim, did not choose:
78:68 But made choice of the tribe of Judah, The mountain of Zion, which he loved;
78:69 And built, like the heights, his sanctuary, Like the earth, he founded it to times age-abiding.
78:70 And made choice of David his servant, And took him from among the folds of the sheep:
78:71 From after the sucking ewes, he brought him in,—To be shepherd to Jacob his people, And to Israel, his inheritance.
78:72 So he did shepherd them, according to the singleness of his heart, And, with the discernment of his hands, used he to guide them.

83:1 O God, Do not keep quiet, Do not hold thy peace, Neither be thou still, O GOD!
83:2 For lo! thine enemies, are tumultuous, And, they who hate thee, have lifted up the head;
83:3 Against thy people, they craftily devise a secret plot, And conspire against thy treasured ones.
83:4 They have said—Come, and let us wipe them out from being a nation, That the name of Israel may be remembered no more.
83:5 For they have taken counsel with one heart, Against thee—a covenant, would they solemnize—
83:6 The tents of Edom, and the Ishmaelites, of Moab and the Hagarenes;
83:7 Gebal and Ammon, and Amalek, The Philistines, with the dwellers in Tyre;
83:8 Even Assyria hath joined herself with them, They have become an arm to the sons of Lot. [Selah.]
83:9 Make them like Midian, like Sisera, like Jabin, by the torrent of Kishon;
83:10 They perished at En-dor, They become manure for the soil!
83:11 Make them—their nobles—like Oreb and like Zeeb, And, like Zebah and like Zalmunna, all their princes:
83:12 Who said—Let us take a possession for ourselves, The pastures of God!
83:13 O my God, make them, As whirling [dust], As chaff before a wind;
83:14 As a fire burneth a forest,—And as a flame setteth mountains ablaze,
83:15 So, wilt thou pursue them with thy tempest,—And, with thy storm-wind, wilt terrify them:
83:16 Fill thou their faces with dishonour, That men may seek thy Name, O Yahweh;
83:17 Let them turn pale, and be terrified to futurity, Yea let them blush, and perish:
83:18 That men may know that, thou, Whose Name alone is Yahweh, Art Most High over all the earth.

89:1 The lovingkindnesses of Yahweh, age-abidingly will I sing, To generation after generation, will I make known thy faithfulness with my mouth.
89:2 For I said, To times age-abiding, shall lovingkindness be built up, As for the heavens, thou wilt establish thy faithfulness therein.
89:3 I have solemnised a covenant, for my chosen one, I have sworn unto David my servant:
89:4 Unto times age-abiding, will I establish thy seed, And will build up, unto generation after generation, thy throne. [Selah.]
89:5 So shall the heavens praise thy wondrousness, O Yahweh,—Yea, thy faithfulness, in the convocation of holy ones.
89:6 For whom, in the skies, can one compare unto Yahweh? [Or] can one liken unto Yahweh, among the sons of the mighty?
89:7 A GOD inspiring awe in the circle of the holy ones, exceedingly, And to be reverenced above all who are round about him.
89:8 O Yahweh, God of hosts! Who, like thee, is mighty, O Yah! With thy faithfulness round about thee:
89:9 Thou, rulest over the swelling of the sea, When the rolling waves thereof lift themselves, Thou, dost bid them be still:
89:10 Thou, hast crushed—as one slain—Rahab, With thy strong arm, hast thou scattered thy foes.
89:11 Thine, are the heavens, Yea, thine, the earth, The world and the fulness thereof, Thou, didst found them;
89:12 The north and the south, Thou, didst create them,—Tabor and Hermon, with thy Name, shall shout for joy:
89:13 Thine is an arm with might, Strong is thy hand, High is thy right hand;
89:14 Righteousness and justice, are the establishing of thy throne, Lovingkindness and faithfulness, go before thy face.
89:15 How happy are the people who know the joyful sound! O Yahweh! in the light of thy countenance, shall they firmly march along;
89:16 In thy Name, shall they exult all the day, And, in thy righteousness, shall they be exalted.
89:17 For, the beauty of their strength, thou art, And, in thine acceptance, shall our horns be exalted.
89:18 For, to Yahweh, belongeth our Shield, And, to the Holy One of Israel, belongeth our King.
89:19 Then spakest thou in vision of thy men of lovingkindness, and saidst—I have laid help upon a mighty one, I have exalted one chosen from among the people;
89:20 I have found David my servant, With mine own holy oil, have I anointed him;
89:21 With whom my hand shall be firm, Yea, mine arm, shall strengthen him;
89:22 No foe shall make exactions on him, Nor shall, a son of perversity, humiliate him;
89:23 And I will shatter, from before him, his adversaries, And, them who hate him, will I smite;
89:24 And, my faithfulness and my lovingkindness, shall be with him, And, in my Name, exalted shall be his horn;
89:25 And I will set, in the sea, his hand, And, in the rivers, his right hand;
89:26 He, shall cry out unto me, My Father, thou art, My GOD, and my Rock of Salvation!
89:27 Yea, I, will appoint him, firstborn, Most High to the kings of the earth!
89:28 Age-abidingly, will I keep for him my lovingkindness, And, my covenant, hath been made steadfast for him;
89:29 Therefore will I appoint, to futurity, his seed, And his throne as the days of the heavens.
89:30 If his sons forsake my law, And, in my regulations, do not walk;
89:31 If, my statutes, they profane, And, my commandments, do not keep:
89:32 Then will I punish, with a rod, their transgression; And, with stripes, their iniquity:
89:33 But, my lovingkindness, will I not frustrate from them, Neither will I falsify my faithfulness;
89:34 I will not violate my covenant, And that which hath proceeded out of my lips, will I not alter:
89:35 One thing, have I sworn by my holiness, Verily, to David, will I not lie;
89:36 His seed, age-abidingly, shall remain, And, his throne, be like the sun before me;
89:37 Like the moon, shall it be established unto times age-abiding, And, a witness, in the skies, hath been made sure. [Selah.]
89:38 Yet, thou thyself, hast cast off, and rejected, Thou hast been wroth with thine Anointed One!
89:39 Thou hast cast down the covenant of thy Servant, Thou hast profaned, to the earth, his crown;
89:40 Thou hast broken down all his defenses, Thou hast laid his fortresses in ruins;
89:41 All the passers by the way, have plundered him, He hath become a reproach to his neighbours;
89:42 Thou hast raised the right hand of his adversaries, Thou hast gladdened all his enemies;
89:43 Yea thou hast turned the edge of his sword, Neither hast thou caused him to stand in the battle;
89:44 Thou hast brought to an end his splendour, And, his throne—to the ground, hast thou hurled;
89:45 Thou hast shortened the days of his youths,—Thou hast covered him with shame. [Selah.]
89:46 How long, O Yahweh, Wilt thou hide thyself utterly? Shall thine indignation, burn like fire?
89:47 Remember how short-lived, I, am, Wherefore, in vain, hast thou created all the sons of Adam?
89:48 Who is the man that shall live, and not see death? That can deliver his soul from the hand of hades. [Selah.]
89:49 Where are thy former lovingkindnesses, O My Lord? Thou didst swear unto David, in thy faithfulness!
89:50 Remember, O My Lord, the reproach of thy servants, I have carried in my bosom the insult of the peoples:
89:51 In that thy foes have reproached, O Yahweh, In that they have reproached the footsteps of thine Anointed One!
89:52 Blessed be Yahweh to times age-abiding, Amen, and Amen!

91:1 He that dwelleth in the secret place of the Most High, Under the shadow of the Almighty, will tarry,
91:2 Saying of Yahweh—My refuge and my fortress, My God, in whom I will trust.
91:3 For, he, will rescue thee, From the snare of the fowler, From the destructive pestilence.
91:4 With his pinion, will he cover thee, And, under his wings, shalt thou seek refuge, A shield and buckler, is his faithfulness.
91:5 Thou shalt not be afraid, Of the dread of the night, Of the arrow that flieth by day;
91:6 Of the pestilence that, in darkness, doth walk, Of the plague that layeth waste at noonday.
91:7 There shall fall, at thy side, a thousand, Yea, myriads, at thy right hand, Unto thee, shall it not come nigh;
91:8 Save only, with thine own eyes, shalt thou discern, And, the recompense of the lawless, shalt thou see.
91:9 Because, thou, [hast made] Yahweh, my refuge,—The Most High, thou hast made thy dwelling-place,
91:10 There shall not be sent unto thee misfortune, Nor shall, plague, come near into thy tent;
91:11 For, his messengers, will he charge concerning thee, To keep thee, in all thy ways;
91:12 On hands, will they bear thee up, Lest thou strike, against a stone, thy foot;
91:13 On the lion and adder, shalt thou tread, Shalt trample on young lion and crocodile.
91:14 Because, on me, he hath set firm his love, Therefore will I deliver him, I will set him on high, Because he hath known my Name;
91:15 He shall call me, and I will answer him, With him, will, I, be, in distress, I will rescue him, and will honour him;
91:16 With length of days, will I satisfy him, And will show him my salvation.

92:1 It is good to give thanks to Yahweh, And to sing praises unto thy Name, O Most High;
92:2 To declare, in the morning, thy lovingkindness, And thy faithfulness at night;
92:3 Upon an instrument of ten strings, and upon a harp, With resounding music on the lyre.
92:4 For thou hast made me glad, O Yahweh, in thy doing, In the works of thy hands, will I shout for joy.
92:5 How great have grown thy works, Yahweh, [How] very deep are laid thy plans!
92:6 A man that is brutish, cannot know, And, a dullard, cannot discern this:—
92:7 When the lawless do thrive like grass, And all the workers of iniquity have blossomed, It is that they may be destroyed for ever.
92:8 But, thou, shalt be on high age-abidingly, O Yahweh.
92:9 For lo! thine enemies, Yahweh, For lo! thine enemies, shall perish, They shall be scattered—all the workers of iniquity;
92:10 But thou wilt exalt, as [those of] the buffalo, my horn, I have been anointed, with fresh oil.
92:11 So hath mine eye descried them who were lying in wait for me,—Of my wicked assailants, mine ears, shall hear.
92:12 The righteous, like the palm-tree, shall thrive, Like the cedar in Lebanon, shall he grow;
92:13 They who are planted in the house of Yahweh, In the courts of our God, shall flourish;
92:14 Still shall they bear fruit in old age, Vigorous and fresh, shall they be:
92:15 To declare that upright is Yahweh, My Rock, and no perversity in him.

96:1 Sing to Yahweh, a song that is new, Sing to Yahweh, all the earth;
96:2 Sing to Yahweh, bless ye his Name,—Tell the tidings, from day to day, of his salvation:
96:3 Recount, Among the nations, his glory, Among all the peoples, his wonders.
96:4 For great is Yahweh, and worthy to be mightily praised, To be revered is he above all gods;
96:5 For, all the gods of the peoples, are things of nought—But, Yahweh, made, the heavens.
96:6 Praise and majesty, are before him, Strength and beauty, are in his sanctuary.
96:7 Give to Yahweh, ye families of the peoples, Give to Yahweh, glory and strength;
96:8 Give to Yahweh, the glory of his Name, Bring a present, and enter his courts;
96:9 Bow down to Yahweh, in the adornment of holiness, Be in anguish at his presence, all the earth!
96:10 Say among the nations, Yahweh, hath become King, Surely he hath fixed the world, it shall not be shaken, He will judge the peoples with equity.
96:11 Let the heavens rejoice, and the earth exult, Let the sea roar, and the fulness thereof;
96:12 Let the field, leap for joy, and all that is therein, Then, shall all the trees of the forest, shout in triumph,
96:13 Before Yahweh, for he is coming, For he is coming to judge the earth,—He will judge the world, in righteousness, And the peoples, in his faithfulness.

text.NABRE:
96:1 Psalm 96 God of the Universe I - Sing to the LORD a new song; sing to the LORD, all the earth.
96:2 Sing to the LORD, bless his name; proclaim his salvation day after day.
96:3 Tell his glory among the nations; among all peoples, his marvelous deeds.
96:4 II - For great is the LORD and highly to be praised, to be feared above all gods.
96:5 For the gods of the nations are idols, but the LORD made the heavens.
96:6 Splendor and power go before him; power and grandeur are in his holy place.
96:7 III - Give to the LORD, you families of nations, give to the LORD glory and might;
96:8 give to the LORD the glory due his name! Bring gifts and enter his courts;
96:9 bow down to the LORD, splendid in holiness. Tremble before him, all the earth;
96:10 declare among the nations: The LORD is king. The world will surely stand fast, never to be shaken. He rules the peoples with fairness.
96:11 IV - Let the heavens be glad and the earth rejoice; let the sea and what fills it resound;
96:12 let the plains be joyful and all that is in them. Then let all the trees of the forest rejoice
96:13 before the LORD who comes, who comes to govern the earth, To govern the world with justice and the peoples with faithfulness.

text.Rotherham:
98:1 Sing to Yahweh, a song that is new, For, wonderful things, hath he done, His own right hand and his holy arm, have brought him salvation.
98:2 Yahweh, hath made known, his salvation, Before the eyes of the nations, hath he revealed his righteousness;
98:3 He hath remembered his lovingkindness and his faithfulness towards the house of Israel,—All the ends of the earth, have seen, the salvation of our God.
98:4 Shout aloud to Yahweh, all the earth, Break forth and make a joyful noise and sweep the strings;
98:5 Sweep the strings to Yahweh, With the lyre, With the lyre, and the voice of melody;
98:6 With trumpets and the sound of a horn, Shout aloud, before the king—Yahweh.
98:7 Let the sea, roar, and the fulness thereof, The world, and they who dwell therein;
98:8 Let, the floods, clap their hands, Together, let, the mountains, make a joyful noise,
98:9 Before Yahweh, for he is coming—to judge the earth,—He will judge the world, in righteousness, And the peoples, with equity.

text.NABRE:
100:1 Psalm 100 Processional Hymn - A psalm of thanksgiving. Shout joyfully to the LORD, all you lands;
100:2 serve the LORD with gladness; come before him with joyful song.
100:3 Know that the LORD is God, he made us, we belong to him, we are his people, the flock he shepherds.
100:4 Enter his gates with thanksgiving, his courts with praise. Give thanks to him, bless his name;
100:5 good indeed is the LORD, His mercy endures forever, his faithfulness lasts through every generation.

text.Rotherham:
101:1 Of lovingkindness and of justice, will I sing! Unto thee, O Yahweh, will I touch the strings!
101:2 I will behave myself wisely in a blameless way, When wilt thou come in unto me? I will walk to and fro in the blamelessness of my heart,—in the midst of my house:
101:3 I will not set before mine eyes, a vile thing,—The doing of them who fall away, I hate, It shall not cleave unto me;
101:4 A perverse heart, shall depart from me, A maker of mischief, will I not acknowledge;
101:5 He that uttereth slander in secret against his friend, him, will I root out; One of lofty eyes, and of an ambitious heart, him shall I not be able to endure.
101:6 Mine eyes, shall be upon the faithful of the land, That they may dwell with me,—he that walketh in a blameless way, he, shall attend me.
101:7 There shall not dwell in the midst of my house, One who worketh deceit,—he that speaketh falsehoods, shall not be established before mine eyes;
101:8 Morning by morning, will I uproot, All the lawless ones of the land, That I may cut off, out of the city of Yahweh—All the workers of iniquity.

103:1 Bless, O my soul, Yahweh,—And all that is within me, his holy Name;
103:2 Bless, O my soul, Yahweh, And forget not all his dealings:—
103:3 Who forgiveth all thine iniquity, Who healeth all thy diseases;
103:4 Who redeemeth, from destruction, thy life, Who crowneth thee, with lovingkindness and compassion:
103:5 Who satisfieth, with good, thine age, Thy youth, reneweth itself like an eagle.
103:6 Yahweh is one, who executeth righteousness, Yea vindication for all the oppressed.
103:7 Who made known his ways unto Moses, unto the sons of Israel, his doings.
103:8 Compassionate and gracious, is Yahweh,—Slow to anger and abundant in lovingkindness.
103:9 Not perpetually, will he contend, Nor age-abidingly, retain anger;
103:10 Not according to our sins, hath he dealt with us, Nor according to our iniquities, hath he treated us.
103:11 For, as the heavens are exalted over the earth, His lovingkindness hath prevailed over them who revere him;
103:12 As far as East from West, Hath he put far from us, our transgressions;
103:13 Like the compassion of a father for his children, Is, the compassion of Yahweh, for them who revere him;
103:14 For, he, knoweth how we are formed, He is mindful that, dust, we are.
103:15 As for man, like grass, are his days, Like the blossom of the field, so, doth he blossom;
103:16 For, a wind, hath passed over it, and it is gone, And its own place is acquainted with it no more.
103:17 But, the lovingkindness of Yahweh, is from one age even to another, Upon them who revere him, And his righteousness, to children’s children:—
103:18 To such as keep his covenant, And remember his precepts, to do them.
103:19 Yahweh, in the heavens, hath established his throne, And, his kingdom, over all, hath dominion.
103:20 Bless Yahweh, ye messengers of his,—Heroes of vigour, doing his word, To hearken [again] to the voice of his word;
103:21 Bless Yahweh, all ye his hosts, Attendants of his, doing his pleasure;
103:22 Bless Yahweh, all ye his works, In all places of his dominion, Bless, O my soul, Yahweh.

104:1 Bless, O my soul, Yahweh,—Yahweh, my God, thou art exceedingly great, With honour and majesty, hast thou clothed thyself,
104:2 Putting on light, as a robe, Stretching out the heavens, as a curtain;
104:3 Building, in the waters, his upper chambers,—Who maketh clouds his chariot, Who passeth along on the wings of the wind;
104:4 Making His messengers, winds, His attendants, a flaming fire;
104:5 He hath fixed the earth on its foundations, It is not to be shaken, to times age-abiding and beyond.
104:6 With the resounding deep—as a garment, hast thou covered it, Above the mountains, stand the waters;
104:7 At thy rebuke, they flee, At the voice of thy thunder, they hurry away;
104:8 Mountains rise, Valleys sink, Unto the place which thou hast fixed for them;
104:9 Bounds, hast thou set, which they are not to pass over, They are not to return to cover the earth.
104:10 Who hast sent forth springs, through the torrent-beds, Between the mountains, they flow along;
104:11 They give drink, to every wild beast of the field, The wild asses do break their thirst.
104:12 Over them, the bird of the heavens settleth down, From amidst the foliage, they utter a voice.
104:13 Who watereth the mountains out of his upper chambers, Out of the fruit of thy works, thou satisfiest the earth.
104:14 Who causeth the grass to shoot forth for the cattle, And the herb, for the service of man, That he may bring forth food out of the earth;
104:15 And, wine, may rejoice the heart of man, Making radiant his well-nourished face,—And, food, may, the heart of man, sustain.
104:16 Satisfied are, The trees of Yahweh, The cedars of Lebanon, which he hath planted;
104:17 Where the birds build their nests, The stork, in the fir-trees, hath her house;
104:18 The high mountains, are for the chamois, The crags, are a refuge for the conies.
104:19 He hath made the moon for seasons, And, the sun, knoweth his place for entering in.
104:20 Thou causest darkness, and it becometh night, Therein, creepeth forth, Every wild beast of the forest;
104:21 The young lions, roaring for prey, And seeking, from GOD, their food.
104:22 The sun ariseth, they withdraw themselves, And, in their lairs, lay them down.
104:23 Man goeth forth to his work, And to his labour, until evening.
104:24 How thy works abound, O Yahweh! All of them—in wisdom, hast thou made, The earth is full of thy possession:—
104:25 This sea here, is great and broad on both hands,—Wherein are creeping things, even without number, Living things, small with great;
104:26 There, ships, sail along, This sea-monster, thou hast formed to sport therein;
104:27 All of them, for thee, do wait, That thou mayest give them their food in its season;
104:28 Thou givest unto them, they gather, Thou openest thy hand, they are satisfied with good.
104:29 Thou hidest thy face, they are dismayed, Thou withdrawest their spirit, They cease to breathe, And, unto their own dust, do they return:
104:30 Thou sendest forth thy spirit, they are created, And thou renewest the face of the ground.
104:31 Be thy glory, O Yahweh, to times age-abiding, Let Yahweh rejoice in his own works:
104:32 Who looketh at the earth, and it trembleth, He toucheth the mountains, and they smoke.
104:33 I will sing to Yahweh, as long as I live! Yea I will touch the strings to my God, while I continue;
104:34 Pleasing unto him, be my meditation, I, will rejoice in Yahweh.
104:35 Sinners shall be consumed out of the earth And, the lawless, no more, shall exist,—Bless, O my soul, Yahweh, Praise ye Yah!

105:1 Give ye thanks to Yahweh, Call upon his Name, Make known, among the peoples, his doings;
105:2 Sing ye to him, Make ye music to him, Speak ye of all his wonders.
105:3 Make your boast in his holy Name, Joyful be the heart of them who are seeking Yahweh.
105:4 Search out Yahweh and his strength, Seek diligently his face at all times.
105:5 Remember his wonders which he hath done, His portents, and the just decisions of his mouth.
105:6 O ye Seed of Abraham—his servants, Sons of Jacob—his chosen ones:
105:7 Yahweh himself, is our God, Through all the land, are his just decision.
105:8 He hath remembered, unto times age-abiding, his covenant, The word he commanded, to a thousand generations;
105:9 Which he solemnised with Abraham, and his oath, to Isaac;
105:10 And confirmed it unto Jacob for a statute, To Israel, as a covenant age-abiding;
105:11 Saying, To thee, will I give the land of Canaan, As your inherited portion;
105:12 While as yet they were men easily counted,—A very few, and sojourners therein;
105:13 And they wandered from nation to nation, From a kingdom, to another people.
105:14 He suffered no son of earth to oppress them, And reproved—for their sakes—[even] kings!
105:15 Ye may not touch mine Anointed ones, And, to my Prophets, may ye do no wrong.
105:16 Then called he a famine over the land, All the staff of bread, he brake;
105:17 He sent before them a man, For a slave, was he sold—[even] Joseph;
105:18 They forced, into a fetter, his foot, Into the iron, entered his soul;
105:19 Until the time when his word came to pass, Speech of Yahweh, proved him;
105:20 The king sent, and set him free, One having dominion over peoples, yet loosed he his bonds;
105:21 He appointed him lord to his household, And one having dominion over all he possessed;
105:22 That he might bind his rulers as he pleased, And, his elders, he might embue with wisdom.
105:23 So Israel came into Egypt, And, Jacob, sojourned in the land of Ham;
105:24 And he made his people exceeding fruitful,—And caused them to become stronger than their adversaries.
105:25 He let them turn their heart—To hate his people, To deal treacherously with his servants;
105:26 He sent Moses his servant, Aaron, whom he had chosen.
105:27 He set among them his threatening signs, And his wonders, in the land of Ham;
105:28 He sent darkness, and made it dark, But they rebelled against his words;
105:29 He turned their waters into blood, And so caused their fish to die;
105:30 Their land swarmed with frogs, In the chambers of their kings!
105:31 He spake, and there came in the gad-fly, Gnats, in all their bounds;
105:32 He made their showers—hail, A fire flaming throughout their land;
105:33 And he smote their vines, and their fig-trees, And brake in pieces the trees of their bounds;
105:34 He spake—then came the swarming locust,—The devouring locust, and that without number;
105:35 And devoured all the herbage in their land, And devoured the fruit of their ground.
105:36 Then smote he every firstborn in their land, The beginning of all their strength;
105:37 Thus brought he them forth, with silver and gold, Nor was there, throughout his tribes, one that faltered;
105:38 Egypt rejoiced when they went out, For the dread of them had fallen upon them.
105:39 He spread out a cloud as a covering, And fire, to give light by night,
105:40 They asked, and he brought in the quail,—And, with the bread of the heavens, he satisfied them;
105:41 He opened the rock, and there gushed forth waters, They flowed along, through parched places, as a river;
105:42 For he remembered his holy word, With Abraham his servant.
105:43 Thus brought he forth his people with gladness,—With shouts of triumph, his chosen ones;
105:44 And gave them, the lands of the nations, And, of the toil of the peoples, took they possession:
105:45 In order that they might observe his statutes, And, over his laws, might keep watch, Praise ye Yah.

106:1 Praise ye Yah, Give ye thanks to Yahweh—For he is good, For age-abiding, is his lovingkindness.
106:2 Who can relate the mighty deeds of Yahweh? can cause to be heard, all his praise?
106:3 How happy! They who observe justice, He that executeth righteousness at all times.
106:4 Remember me, O Yahweh, when thou acceptest thy people, Visit me, with thy salvation;
106:5 That I may look upon the welfare of thy chosen ones, That I may rejoice in the joy of thy nation, That I may glory, with thine inheritance.
106:6 We have sinned—with our fathers, We have acted perversely, we have committed lawlessness;
106:7 Our fathers, in Egypt, understood not thy wonders, They remembered not the abounding of thy lovingkindnesses, but rebelled by the sea—at the Red Sea.
106:8 Yet he saved them, for the sake of his Name, to make known his mighty power;
106:9 So he rebuked the Red Sea, and it dried up, And he led them through deeps, as pasture-land;
106:10 And saved them from the hand of one full of hatred, And redeemed them out of the hand of the foe;
106:11 So the waters covered their adversaries, Not one from among them, was left.
106:12 They believed therefore in his words, They sang his praise.
106:13 Soon forgat they his works,—They waited not for his counsel;
106:14 But lusted a lust in the desert, and tested GOD in the waste.
106:15 So he gave them their request, but sent leanness into their soul.
106:16 And they became jealous of Moses in the camp,—of Aaron the holy one of Yahweh;
106:17 The earth opened and engulfed Dathan, and covered up the assembly of Abiram;
106:18 Then was kindled a fire in their assembly,—a flame, consumed the lawless ones.
106:19 They made a calf in Horeb,—and bowed down to a molten image;
106:20 Thus changed they my glory, for the similitude of an ox that eateth grass.
106:21 They forgat GOD their saviour, who had done great things in Egypt:
106:22 Wonders in the land of Ham, Terrible things by the Red Sea.
106:23 Then would he have bidden to destroy them,—had not Moses his chosen, stood in the breach before him, To turn back his wrath from destroying.
106:24 And they refused the delightful land, They believed not his word;
106:25 But murmured in their tents,—They hearkened not unto the voice of Yahweh.
106:26 So he lifted up his hand unto them, that he would let them fall in the desert;
106:27 And would disperse their seed among the nations, and would scatter them throughout the lands.
106:28 Yet they let themselves be bound to Baal-peor,—and did eat sacrifices to the dead:
106:29 So they provoked to anger by their doings, and a plague, made a breach among them.
106:30 Then stood up Phinehas, and interposed, and stayed was the plague:
106:31 So it was counted unto him, for righteousness, To generation after generation, unto times age abiding.
106:32 And they provoked by the waters of Meribah,—And it fared ill with Moses, for their sakes;
106:33 For they embittered his spirit, and he spake rashly with his lips.
106:34 They destroyed not the peoples of which Yahweh had spoken to them;
106:35 But had fellowship with the nations, and learned their doings;
106:36 Yea they served their idols, and they became to them a snare:
106:37 Yea they sacrificed their sons and their daughters to mischievous demons;
106:38 And poured out innocent blood, the blood of their sons and their daughters, whom they sacrificed to the idols of Canaan, And the land was polluted with blood-shed;
106:39 And they became unclean by their works, and became unchaste in their doings.
106:40 Then was kindled the anger of Yahweh with his people, and he abhorred his own inheritance.
106:41 So he delivered them up into the hand of the nations, And they who hated them, had dominion over them;
106:42 And their enemies oppressed them, And they were bowed down under their hand.
106:43 Many times, did he rescue them,—But, they, rebelled by their counsel, and sank low in their iniquity.
106:44 Then looked he on the distress which befell them,—when he heard their loud cry;
106:45 Then remembered he, for them, his covenant, and was moved to pity, according to the abounding of his lovingkindnesses;
106:46 And granted them compassion before all their captors.
106:47 Save us, O Yahweh our God, and gather us from among the nations, That we may give thanks unto thy holy Name, That we may triumph aloud in thy praise.
106:48 Blessed be Yahweh, God of Israel, from one age even unto another, And all the people, shall say, Amen! Praise ye Yah!

107:1 O give thanks to Yahweh—For he is good, For, age-abiding, is his lovingkindness.
107:2 Let the redeemed of Yahweh say, Whom he hath redeemed from the hand of the adversary;
107:3 And, out of the lands, hath gathered them—From the east and from the west, From the north and from the south.
107:4 They wandered about in the desert—in a waste, Way to a city to dwell in, found they none;
107:5 Hungry—yea thirsty, their soul, within them, fainted:
107:6 Then made they outcry to Yahweh, in their peril, Out of their distresses, he rescued them;
107:7 And led them by a straight road, That they might journey to a city to dwell in.
107:8 Let them give thanks to Yahweh for his lovingkindness, and for his wonderful dealings with the sons of men;
107:9 For he hath satisfied the longing soul, and, the famished soul, hath he filled with good.
107:10 The dwellers in darkness and death-shade, bound with oppression and iron;
107:11 Because they had rebelled against the sayings of GOD,—and, the counsel of the Most High, they had spurned;
107:12 And he bowed down, with labour, their heart, They staggered, with no one to help,
107:13 Then made they outcry to Yahweh in their peril, Out of their distresses, he saved them;
107:14 He brought them forth out of darkness and death-shade, and, their fetters, he tare off.
107:15 Let them give thanks to Yahweh for his lovingkindness, and for his wonderful dealings with the sons of men!
107:16 For he brake in pieces the doors of bronze, And, the bars of iron, he hewed asunder.
107:17 The perverse, by reason of their transgression, and on account of their iniquities, are afflicted;
107:18 All manner of food, their soul abhorreth, and so they draw near unto the gates of death,
107:19 Then make they outcry to Yahweh in their peril, and, out of their distresses, he saveth them.
107:20 He sendeth his word, and healeth them, and delivereth them from their graves.
107:21 Let them give thanks to Yahweh for his lovingkindness, and for his wonderful dealings with the sons of men!
107:22 Yea let them sacrifice the sacrifices of thanksgiving, and recount his works with a shout.
107:23 Men who go down to the sea, in ships, doing business through mighty waters;
107:24 They, see the works of Yahweh, and his wonders in the deep;
107:25 And he speaketh, and there ariseth a tempestuous wind, which lifteth on high its rolling waves;
107:26 They mount the heavens, they descend the roaring deeps, their soul, by trouble, dissolveth;
107:27 They reel and stagger, like a drunken man, and, all their wisdom, is engulfed,
107:28 Then make they outcry to Yahweh in their peril, and, out of their distresses, he bringeth them forth,
107:29 He calmeth the storm to a whisper, and silent are their rolling waves:
107:30 Then are they glad, because they are hushed, And he guideth them unto their desired haven.
107:31 Let them give thanks to Yahweh for his lovingkindness, and for his wonderful dealings with the sons of men!
107:32 Yea let them extol him in the convocation of the people, and, in the seated company of elders, let them praise him.
107:33 He turneth Rivers into a desert, and, Springs of Water, into thirsty ground,
107:34 A Land of Fruit, into a waste of salt, For the wickedness of them who dwell therein.
107:35 He turneth A Desert, into a pool of water, and, A Parched Land into springs of water;
107:36 And hath caused the famished to dwell there, And they have built them a city to dwell in;
107:37 And have sown fields, and planted vineyards, and made them fruits of increase:
107:38 Thus hath he blessed them, and they have multiplied greatly, And, their cattle, he maketh not few.
107:39 So have they become few and been brought low, By oppression, misfortune, and sorrow;
107:40 He poureth contempt upon nobles, and causeth them to wander in a pathless waste;
107:41 But he hath set the needy on high from affliction, and made families, like a flock:—
107:42 The upright seeth and is glad, And, all perverseness, hath closed her mouth.
107:43 Who is wise? then let him observe these things! and diligently consider the lovingkindness of Yahweh.

109:1 O God of my praise, do not be silent;
109:2 For, the mouth of the lawless one and the mouth of the deceiver, against me, are open, They have spoken to me with false tongue;
109:3 And, with words of hatred, have they surrounded me, and have made war upon me without cause:
109:4 For my love, they have been accusing me, while, I, was at prayer:
109:5 Yea they have returned unto me—Evil for good; and, Hatred for my love.
109:6 Set in charge over him, one who is lawless, and let, an accuser, stand at his right hand;
109:7 When he is judged, let him go out condemned, and let, his own petition, become a sin;
109:8 Let his days become few, his overseership, let another take;
109:9 Let his children become fatherless, and his wife a widow;
109:10 Let his children, wander about, and beg, Let them be driven out of their ruins;
109:11 Let the creditor take aim at all that he hath, and let strangers prey on the fruit of his toil;
109:12 Let him have no one to continue lovingkindness, and there be none to favour his fatherless children;
109:13 Let his posterity be for cutting off, In another generation, let their name be wiped out;
109:14 Remembered be the iniquity of his fathers against Yahweh, and, the sin of his mother, let it not be wiped out;
109:15 Let them be before Yahweh continually, and let the memory of them, be cut off out of the earth.
109:16 Because that he remembered not to show lovingkindness, but pursued the man that was oppressed and needy, that, the downhearted, he might slay.
109:17 Because he loved cursing, May it have come upon him, Because he delighted not in blessing, May it have kept far from him;
109:18 Because he clothed himself in cursing as his outer garment, therefore may it have entered like water into his inward part, and like oil into his bones;
109:19 Be it his, as a garment he shall wrap round him, and for a girdle he shall, at all times, gird on:
109:20 This, be the reward of mine accusers, from Yahweh, even of them who are speaking wrongfully against my life.
109:21 But, thou, Yahweh, Adonay, deal effectually with me, for the sake of thy Name, Since good is thy lovingkindness, O rescue me;
109:22 For, oppressed and needy, I am, and, my heart, is wounded within me.
109:23 As a shadow when it stretcheth out, I am gone, I am shaken off like the locust;
109:24 My knees, tremble from fasting, and, my flesh, faileth of fatness:
109:25 So, I, am become a reproach for them, They see me, they shake their head.
109:26 Help me! O Yahweh my God, Save me, according to thy lovingkindness:
109:27 That they may know that, Thine own hand, this is, Thou, Yahweh, hast done it.
109:28 They, may curse if, thou, wilt bless,—Mine assailants, shall be ashamed, but, thy servant, shall rejoice;
109:29 Mine accusers shall be clothed with confusion, and shall wrap about them, like a cloak, their own shame.
109:30 I will thank Yahweh loudly with my mouth, Yea, in the midst of multitudes, will I praise him;
109:31 Because he standeth at the right hand of the needy, To save, from them who would pass sentence on his life.

112:1 Praise ye Yah! How happy is the man who revereth Yahweh, In his commandments, delighteth he greatly;
112:2 Mighty in the earth, shall be his seed, The generation of the upright, shall be blessed;
112:3 Wealth and riches, shall be in his house, and, his righteousness, standeth for aye.
112:4 Risen—in darkness, is light to the upright, The gracious and compassionate and righteous.
112:5 Well for a man showing favour and lending! He shall sustain his affairs with justice.
112:6 Surely, unto times age-abiding, shall he not be shaken, In remembrance, age-abiding, shall the righteous one remain;
112:7 Of evil tidings, shall he not be afraid, Established is his heart, led to trust in Yahweh;
112:8 Upheld is his heart, he shall not be afraid, until that he gazeth on his foes.
112:9 He hath scattered abroad, he hath given to the needy, His righteousness, standeth for aye, His horn, shall be exalted in honour.
112:10 The lawless one, shall see, and be indignant, his teeth, will he gnash and melt away, The craving of the lawless, shall vanish.

113:1 Praise ye Yah! Praise, O ye servants of Yahweh, Praise the Name of Yahweh;
113:2 Be the Name of Yahweh blessed, henceforth, even to times age-abiding.
113:3 From the rising of the sun unto the going in thereof, Worthy to be praised, is the Name of Yahweh:
113:4 High above all nations, is Yahweh, Above the heavens, his glory.
113:5 Who is like Yahweh our God? that goeth on high to dwell,
113:6 That cometh down low to look, through the heavens and through the earth;
113:7 That raiseth, out of the dust, the poor, From the dunghill, uplifteth the needy;
113:8 To give a seat with nobles, with the nobles of his people!
113:9 Causing the barren woman to dwell in a household, A mother of sons in her joy! Praise ye Yah.

text.JPS1985:
131:1 A song of ascents. Of David. O LORD, my heart is not proud nor my look haughty; I do not aspire to great things or to what is beyond me;
131:2 but I have taught myself to be contented like a weaned child with its mother; like a weaned child am I in my mind.
131:3 O Israel, wait for the LORD now and forever.

133:1 A song of ascents. Of David. How good and how pleasant it is that brothers dwell together.
133:2 It is like fine oil on the head running down onto the beard, the beard of Aaron, that comes down over the collar of his robe;
133:3 like the dew of Hermon that falls upon the mountains of Zion. There the LORD ordained blessing, everlasting life.

text.NRSV:
136:1 O give thanks to the Lord, for he is good, for his steadfast love endures forever.
136:2 O give thanks to the God of gods, for his steadfast love endures forever.
136:3 O give thanks to the Lord of lords, for his steadfast love endures forever;
136:4 who alone does great wonders, for his steadfast love endures forever;
136:5 who by understanding made the heavens, for his steadfast love endures forever;
136:6 who spread out the earth on the waters, for his steadfast love endures forever;
136:7 who made the great lights, for his steadfast love endures forever;
136:8 the sun to rule over the day, for his steadfast love endures forever;
136:9 the moon and stars to rule over the night, for his steadfast love endures forever;
136:10 who struck Egypt through their firstborn, for his steadfast love endures forever;
136:11 and brought Israel out from among them, for his steadfast love endures forever;
136:12 with a strong hand and an outstretched arm, for his steadfast love endures forever;
136:13 who divided the Red Sea in two, for his steadfast love endures forever;
136:14 and made Israel pass through the middle of it, for his steadfast love endures forever;
136:15 but overthrew Pharaoh and his army in the Red Sea, for his steadfast love endures forever;
136:16 who led his people through the wilderness, for his steadfast love endures forever;
136:17 who struck down great kings, for his steadfast love endures forever;
136:18 and killed famous kings, for his steadfast love endures forever;
136:19 Sihon, king of the Amorites, for his steadfast love endures forever;
136:20 and Og, king of Bashan, for his steadfast love endures forever;
136:21 and gave their land as a heritage, for his steadfast love endures forever;
136:22 a heritage to his servant Israel, for his steadfast love endures forever.
136:23 It is he who remembered us in our low estate, for his steadfast love endures forever;
136:24 and rescued us from our foes, for his steadfast love endures forever;
136:25 who gives food to all flesh, for his steadfast love endures forever.
136:26 O give thanks to the God of heaven, for his steadfast love endures forever.

text.JPS1985:
136:1 Praise the LORD; for He is good, His steadfast love is eternal.
136:2 Praise the God of gods, His steadfast love is eternal.
136:3 Praise the Lord of lords, His steadfast love is eternal;
136:4 Who alone works great marvels, His steadfast love is eternal;
136:5 Who made the heavens with wisdom, His steadfast love is eternal;
136:6 Who spread the earth over the water, His steadfast love is eternal;
136:7 Who made the great lights, His steadfast love is eternal;
136:8 the sun to dominate the day, His steadfast love is eternal;
136:9 the moon and the stars to dominate the night, His steadfast love is eternal;
136:10 Who struck Egypt through their first-born, His steadfast love is eternal;
136:11 and brought Israel out of their midst, His steadfast love is eternal;
136:12 with a strong hand and outstretched arm, His steadfast love is eternal;
136:13 Who split apart the Sea of Reeds, His steadfast love is eternal;
136:14 and made Israel pass through it, His steadfast love is eternal;
136:15 Who hurled Pharaoh and his army into the Sea of Reeds, His steadfast love is eternal;
136:16 Who led His people through the wilderness, His steadfast love is eternal;
136:17 Who struck down great kings, His steadfast love is eternal;
136:18 and slew mighty kings— His steadfast love is eternal;
136:19 Sihon, king of the Amorites, His steadfast love is eternal;
136:20 Og, king of Bashan— His steadfast love is eternal;
136:21 and gave their land as a heritage, His steadfast love is eternal;
136:22 a heritage to His servant Israel, His steadfast love is eternal;
136:23 Who took note of us in our degradation, His steadfast love is eternal;
136:24 and rescued us from our enemies, His steadfast love is eternal;
136:25 Who gives food to all flesh, His steadfast love is eternal.
136:26 Praise the God of heaven, His steadfast love is eternal.

text.NABRE:
136:1 Psalm 136 Hymn of Thanksgiving for God’s Everlasting Mercy I - Praise the LORD, for he is good; for his mercy endures forever;
136:2 Praise the God of gods; for his mercy endures forever;
136:3 Praise the Lord of lords; for his mercy endures forever;
136:4 II - Who alone has done great wonders, for his mercy endures forever;
136:5 Who skillfully made the heavens, for his mercy endures forever;
136:6 Who spread the earth upon the waters, for his mercy endures forever;
136:7 Who made the great lights, for his mercy endures forever;
136:8 The sun to rule the day, for his mercy endures forever;
136:9 The moon and stars to rule the night, for his mercy endures forever;
136:10 III - Who struck down the firstborn of Egypt, for his mercy endures forever;
136:11 And led Israel from their midst, for his mercy endures forever;
136:12 With mighty hand and outstretched arm, for his mercy endures forever;
136:13 Who split in two the Red Sea, for his mercy endures forever;
136:14 And led Israel through its midst, for his mercy endures forever;
136:15 But swept Pharaoh and his army into the Red Sea, for his mercy endures forever;
136:16 Who led the people through the desert, for his mercy endures forever;
136:17 IV - Who struck down great kings, for his mercy endures forever;
136:18 Slew powerful kings, for his mercy endures forever;
136:19 Sihon, king of the Amorites, for his mercy endures forever;
136:20 Og, king of Bashan, for his mercy endures forever;
136:21 And made their lands a heritage, for his mercy endures forever;
136:22 A heritage for Israel, his servant, for his mercy endures forever.
136:23 V - The Lord remembered us in our low estate, for his mercy endures forever;
136:24 Freed us from our foes, for his mercy endures forever;
136:25 And gives bread to all flesh, for his mercy endures forever.
136:26 VI - Praise the God of heaven, for his mercy endures forever.

text.JPS1985:
146:1 Hallelujah. Praise the LORD, O my soul!
146:2 I will praise the LORD all my life, sing hymns to my God while I exist.
146:3 Put not your trust in the great, in mortal man who cannot save.
146:4 His breath departs; he returns to the dust; on that day his plans come to nothing.
146:5 Happy is he who has the God of Jacob for his help, whose hope is in the LORD his God,
146:6 maker of heaven and earth, the sea and all that is in them; who keeps faith forever;
146:7 who secures justice for those who are wronged, gives food to the hungry. The LORD sets prisoners free;
146:8 The LORD restores sight to the blind; the LORD makes those who are bent stand straight; the LORD loves the righteous;
146:9 The LORD watches over the stranger; He gives courage to the orphan and widow, but makes the path of the wicked tortuous.
146:10 The LORD shall reign forever, your God, O Zion, for all generations. Hallelujah.

text.Rotherham:
148:1 Praise ye Yah, Praise Yahweh, out of the heavens, Praise him, in the heights;
148:2 Praise him, all his messengers, Praise him, all his host;
148:3 Praise him, sun and moon, Praise him, all ye stars of light;
148:4 Praise him, O ye heavens of heavens, and ye waters that are above the heavens;
148:5 Let them praise the Name of Yahweh, for, he, commanded, and they were created;
148:6 So caused he them to stand perpetually—age-abidingly, A decree, hath he given, and it passeth not beyond.
148:7 Praise Yahweh, out of the earth, sea monsters, and all resounding deeps;
148:8 Fire and hail, snow and vapour, stormy wind, fulfilling his word;
148:9 Ye mountains, and all hills, fruit trees, and all cedars;
148:10 Thou wild-beast, and all ye cattle, crawling creature, and bird of wing;
148:11 Kings of earth, and all peoples, Rulers, and all judges of earth;
148:12 Young men, yea even virgins, elders, and children.
148:13 Let them praise the Name of Yahweh, for lofty is his Name alone, His splendour is over earth and heavens.
148:14 Therefore hath he exalted a horn for his people, a praise for all his men of lovingkindness, for the sons of Israel—a people near him, Praise ye Yah!

text.NABRE:
148:1 Psalm 148 All Creation Summoned to Praise - Hallelujah! I - Praise the LORD from the heavens; praise him in the heights.
148:2 Praise him, all you his angels; give praise, all you his hosts.
148:3 Praise him, sun and moon; praise him, all shining stars.
148:4 Praise him, highest heavens, you waters above the heavens.
148:5 Let them all praise the LORD’s name; for he commanded and they were created,
148:6 Assigned them their station forever, set an order that will never change.
148:7 II - Praise the LORD from the earth, you sea monsters and all the deeps of the sea;
148:8 Lightning and hail, snow and thick clouds, storm wind that fulfills his command;
148:9 Mountains and all hills, fruit trees and all cedars;
148:10 Animals wild and tame, creatures that crawl and birds that fly;
148:11 Kings of the earth and all peoples, princes and all who govern on earth;
148:12 Young men and women too, old and young alike.
148:13 Let them all praise the LORD’s name, for his name alone is exalted, His majesty above earth and heaven.
148:14 He has lifted high the horn of his people; to the praise of all his faithful, the Israelites, the people near to him. Hallelujah!
